<div class="mb-requirement-container">
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15075">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> </span>
      <b>NOTE: </b> The official merit badge pamphlets are now free and
      downloadable
      <a
        href="https://filestore.scouting.org/filestore/Merit_Badge_ReqandRes/Pamphlets/Oceanography.pdf"
        target="_blank"
        >HERE</a
      >
      or can be purchased at the
      <a href="https://www.scoutshop.org/" target="_blank ">Scout Shop.</a>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15093">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 1. </span>
      Name four branches of oceanography. Describe at least five reasons why it
      is important for people to learn about the oceans. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
      <a href="https://youtu.be/NMM_GboBZyc?si=xq_9tR0kLLbCYoQo" target="_blank"
        >What is Oceanography (video)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15094">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 2. </span>
      Explain the following terms: salinity, temperature, and density. Describe
      how these important properties of seawater are measured by an
      oceanographer. Discuss the circulation and currents of the ocean. Describe
      the effects of the oceans on weather and climate. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
      <a href="https://youtu.be/jKWc5oy0NCQ?si=2B4crDCxvuYbGQce" target="_blank"
        >Temperature and Salinity (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/R5-s6O8qyvE" target="_blank"
        >An Ocean in Motion (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/zO2153cJORI" target="_blank"
        >Oceans and Climate (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/T9LTtqcKDw0?si=qNZusyjB_bPjS0UQ" target="_blank"
        >How Do Ocean Currents Affect the Weather Pattern? (video)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15095">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 3. </span>
      Describe the characteristics of ocean waves and do the following:<br /><i
        >Resource:</i
      >
      <a href="https://youtu.be/_LRc6k-clzE?si=_bP0nKjcposT5QV5" target="_blank"
        >How Do Ocean Waves Work? (video)</a
      >
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15095 mb-requirement-id-15099">
        (a) Point out the differences among the storm surge, tsunami, tidal
        wave, and tidal bore. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/wk7RyUReaIA" target="_blank"
          >Tsunami vs Tidal Wave: What's the Difference? (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/ZxYCB4VPVow" target="_blank"
          >What is Storm Surge? (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15095 mb-requirement-id-15100">
        (b) Explain the difference between sea, swell, and surf. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a
          href="https://www.skynews.com.au/australia-news/weather-explained-whats-the-difference-between-seas-and-swell/video/836f58b40244e1a18c28b015033f9792"
          target="_blank"
          >Weather Explained: What's the Difference Between Seas and Swell?
          (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://support.surfline.com/hc/en-us/articles/4410126820891-Difference-between-swell-and-surf"
          target="_blank"
          >Difference Between Swell and Surf (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://www.youtube.com/shorts/qcwAsh9TDvo" target="_blank"
          >The Difference Between SWELL and SURF (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15095 mb-requirement-id-15101">
        (c) Explain how breakers are formed.<br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aXuQC1qRuEM" target="_blank"
          >How Do Waves Break? (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15095 mb-requirement-id-15102">
        (d) Explain what a rip current is, how to avoid them, and what to do if
        you are caught in one. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/lofVgAzut6w?si=At3-3C6bldcYJI5Q"
          target="_blank"
          >New Guide to Spot and Escape a Rip Current (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15076">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 4. </span>
      Draw a cross-section of underwater topography. Name and put on your
      drawing the following: seamount, guyot, rift valley, canyon, trench, and
      oceanic ridge. Compare the depths in the oceans with the heights of
      mountains on land. Show what is meant by: <br /><i>Resources:</i>
      <a
        href="https://www.visualdictionaryonline.com/earth/geology/ocean-floor.php"
        target="_blank"
        >Diagram of Sea Floor (website)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/mAwfTahzbtw" target="_blank"
        >How Deep Does the Ocean Go? (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a
        href="https://youtube.com/shorts/DZ9v54D4mZ8?si=l4pnMMCRDzgxQOpF"
        target="_blank"
        >How Deep the Ocean REALLY Is (video)</a
      >
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15076 mb-requirement-id-15077">
        (a) Continental shelf
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15076 mb-requirement-id-15078">
        (b) Continental slope
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15076 mb-requirement-id-15079">
        (c) Abyssal plain
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15096">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 5. </span>
      List the main salts, gases, and nutrients in seawater. Describe some
      important properties of water. Tell how the animals and plants of the
      ocean affect the chemical composition of seawater. Explain how differences
      in evaporation and precipitation affect the salt content of the oceans.
      <br /><i>Resources:</i>
      <a
        href="https://www.marinebio.net/marinescience/02ocean/swcomposition.htm"
        target="_blank"
        >Seawater Composition (website)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/SPF6cSan6tc" target="_blank"
        >Why is the Sea Salty? (video)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15097">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 6. </span>
      Describe some of the biologically important properties of seawater. Define
      benthos, nekton, and plankton. Name some of the plants and animals that
      make up each of these groups. Describe the place and importance of
      phytoplankton in the oceanic food chain. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
      <a href="https://youtu.be/4cguoY4qTXA" target="_blank"
        >Nekton, Benthos, and Plankton (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/AWfebk0_auY" target="_blank"
        >Feeding the Sea: Phytoplankton Fuel Ocean Life (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/H7sACT0Dx0Q" target="_blank"
        >NASA | Earth Science Week: The Ocean's Green Machines (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a
        href="https://teara.govt.nz/en/video/5354/open-ocean-food-chain"
        target="_blank"
        >Open Ocean Food Chain (website)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15080">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 7. </span>
      Do ONE of the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15080 mb-requirement-id-15081">
        (a) Make a plankton net. Tow the net by a dock, wade with it, hold it in
        a current, or tow it from a rowboat. Do this for about 20 minutes. Save
        the sample. Examine it under a microscope or high-power glass. Identify
        the three most common types of plankton in the sample.<br /><br /><b
          >Note: </b
        >May be done in lakes or streams. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/e-MYhWcWWXw" target="_blank"
          >How to Make a Soda Bottle Plankton Net (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/HBcuGbMc8cU?si=c6sGRZYkRXv9QDtE"
          target="_blank"
          >Make Your Own Plankton Net! (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15080 mb-requirement-id-15082">
        (b) Make a series of models (clay or plaster and wood) of a volcanic
        island. Show the growth of an atoll from a fringing reef through a
        barrier reef. Describe the Darwinian theory of coral reef formation.
        <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/mPA9Ze16lGw?si=pVw56hFgRlnPJtro"
          target="_blank"
          >Coral Reefs: Types and Formation (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/anDSRfSY7LQ" target="_blank"
          >How Coral Reefs are Formed (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15080 mb-requirement-id-15083">
        (c) Measure the water temperature at the surface, midwater, and bottom
        of a body of water four times daily for five consecutive days. You may
        measure depth with a rock tied to a line. Make a Secchi disk to measure
        turbidity (how much suspended sedimentation is in the water). Measure
        the air temperature. Note the cloud cover and roughness of the water.
        Show your findings (air and water temperature, turbidity) on a graph.
        Tell how the water temperature changes with air temperature. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/lr66G09PuKg" target="_blank"
          >How to Make and Use a Secchi Disk (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15080 mb-requirement-id-15084">
        (d) Make a model showing the inshore sediment movement by littoral
        currents, tidal movement, and wave action. Include such formations as
        high and low waterlines, low-tide terrace, berm, and coastal cliffs.
        Show how offshore bars are built up and torn down. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/bfzAeQXhSGk" target="_blank"
          >Longshore Drift Model Demo (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15080 mb-requirement-id-15085">
        (e) Make a wave generator. Show reflection and refraction of waves. Show
        how groins, jetties, and breakwaters affect these patterns. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/9l-tIvvtCPA" target="_blank"
          >DIY Ripple Tank (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/iGuUKRmytLw" target="_blank"
          >Reflecting Waves in a Ripple Tank (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/7wfEczDapHA" target="_blank"
          >Refraction of Waves in a Ripple Tank (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/_eeKpz8oD7E" target="_blank"
          >Coastal Erosion and the Methods Used to Reduce It (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/3yNoy4H2Z-o?si=spekLgWh6z3YHC8W"
          target="_blank"
          >Wave Tank Demonstration (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15080 mb-requirement-id-15086">
        (f) With your counselor's and parent or guardian's approval and
        permission, track and monitor satellite images available on the internet
        for a specific location for three weeks. Describe what you have learned
        to your counselor. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/satellite.php" target="_blank"
          >Weather Satellite Images (website)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15087">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 8. </span>
      Do ONE of the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15087 mb-requirement-id-15091">
        (a) Write a 500-word report on a book about oceanography approved by
        your counselor.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15087 mb-requirement-id-15088">
        (b) Visit one of the following and write a 500-word report about your
        visit.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15088 mb-requirement-id-15089">
        (1) Oceanographic research ship <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/LVDQi5iG99M" target="_blank"
          >Tour of a Research Vessel (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15088 mb-requirement-id-15090">
        (2) Oceanographic institute, marine laboratory, or marine aquarium
        <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/DYI_gw72bk8?si=2GDdWk4RX68hyIK5"
          target="_blank"
          >A Virtual Tour of Bodega Marine Laboratory (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/aaY1fwyjU1U" target="_blank"
          >A Visit to Mote Marine Laboratory &amp; Aquarium (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-15087 mb-requirement-id-15092">
        (c) Explain to your troop, in a five-minute prepared speech "Why
        Oceanography Is Important," or describe "Career Opportunities in
        Oceanography." (Before making your speech, show your speech outline to
        your counselor for approval.)<br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/uFHREUrMLSY" target="_blank"
          >Oceanography Careers (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/N4d6YRKEaxg" target="_blank"
          >How to Work with the Ocean (video)</a
        ><br />
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-15098">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 9. </span>
      Describe four methods that marine scientists use to investigate the ocean,
      underlying geology, and organisms living in the water. <br /><i
        >Resources:</i
      >
      <a href="https://youtu.be/ibPuzpHuAgY" target="_blank"
        >Studying the Ocean EXPLAINED (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/vKzgIyCTY8k?si=gAsNKqiPyHLcwXys" target="_blank"
        >How do Scientists Explore the Deep Sea? (video)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
